# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship] The **2024 Baseball5 Pan American Championship** was the first edition of the Baseball5 Pan American Championship, a Baseball5 tournament organized by WBSC Americas.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship] The championship was held from 27 to 30 June 2024, in the Domo Bolivariano in Barquisimeto, Venezuela and was contested between four national teams.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship] Cuba went undefeated to win the tournament, finishing the opening round 6–0 and defeating Mexico in the championship game.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship] Venezuela, that lost the semifinals against Mexico, claimed the bronze medal.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship] The three teams qualified for the 2024 Baseball5 World Cup in Hong Kong.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-world-cup] The **2024 Baseball5 World Cup** was the second edition of the Baseball5 World Cup, the mixed-gender Baseball5 (B5) world championship organized by the World Baseball Softball Confederation (WBSC).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-world-cup] It was held in Hong Kong from 7 to 12 October 2024.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-world-cup] The tournament was won by Cuba in their second straight Baseball5 World Cup title.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-world-cup] The Cuban team defeated Japan in the championship game, a replay of the 2022 final, 2 sets to 0 to finish the tournament undefeated with a 9–0 record.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-world-cup] Cuban players Briandy Molina and Haila González received the Male MVP and Female MPV of the World Cup.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-world-cup] France claimed the bronze after defeating Venezuela in the bronze medal game, 2 sets to 0.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-world-cup] The 2024 World Cup cost $12 million to host, with the Baseball Association of Hong Kong providing half of the funding.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/2024-baseball5-world-cup] The event has been given "M" Mark status (major sport event) by the Hong Kong government.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] Barquisimeto was founded in 1552 by Juan de Villegas, as a headquarters and to have better control of the territory believed to be rich in gold.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] Its original name was **Nueva Segovia de Barquisimeto** and then it was shortened to just Barquisimeto.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] This city changed locations four times between 1552 and 1563.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] The original settlement was near the Buría River, but moved in 1556 due to frequent floods suffered by inhabitants.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] The second location was in the valley of the Turbio River, where the city stayed until Lope de Aguirre burned it down in 1561.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] The city was rebuilt 102 km (63 mi), but in 1562 they inhabitants asked for permission to move to another site due to strong winds blowing in the place.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] Finally, Barquisimeto was moved to the north plateau of the Turbio River in 1563.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] During the country's independence, Barquisimeto joined the liberation movement and its deputy José Ángel Álamo signed the Independence Act on July 5, 1811.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] In 1929, the city went through a modernization program carried out by General Juan Vicente Gomez.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] He fixed the streets and avenues and buildings were built, like the Jacinto Lara Headquarters, the Government Palace and the Ayacucho Park.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] According to the German adventurer Nikolaus Federmann, the Caquetío aborigines used to call it Variquicimeto, which translates as "ash-colored river", the name with which the natives distinguished the water stream near the city.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] This river was named "Turbio River" by the Spanish conquerors, a name that is still in use today.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] Another possible name origin is due to a red dye called *bariquí*.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] When Juan de Villegas founded it, he named the city "Nueva Segovia de Barquisimeto", but years later it became just "Barquisimeto", a word popularized by Oviedo y Baños in his book *History and Conquest of the Venezuelan Population*.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] The city's modern Cathedral of Our Lady of Mount Carmel is the cathedral of the episcopal see of the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Barquisimeto.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] The Divina Pastora (Divine Shepherdess) is a statue of the Virgin Mary holding the infant Jesus, with a lamb at her side.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] It is considered to be one of the most important religious icons of Venezuela.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] Divina Pastora is the patron saint of the city of Barquisimeto and of the Venezuelan National Militia.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] Divina Pastora is celebrated in a procession on January 14 of each year, when a massive Marian procession occurs, considered to be one of the largest in the world, attracting thousands of pilgrims.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] The statue is removed from its shrine and is carried on the main streets of Barquisimeto in a procession which starts at the Iglesia de la Divina Pastora in Santa Rosa until it reaches the Barquisimeto Cathedral.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] This procession is unlike other mass Marian celebrations in the world, where the image does not leave its temple.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] This procession occurs due to the devotion the people of Barquisimeto have towards it as gratitude towards saving the city from a cholera outbreak that occurred in the city in the 19th century.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] In 2013, 3,000,000 faithful honored the Divina Pastora.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] Barquisimeto is built on the terrace of the same name, on the banks of the Turbio River, about 600 meters (~2000 feet) above sea level, gradually sloping from 520 metres (1,710 feet) in the eastern part of the city to 700 metres (2,300 feet) in the west.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] To the northwest of Barquisimeto there are the Saroche hills (e.g.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] Cerro Copeyal at 1323 meters a.s.l.) and to the northeast there are the Sierra de Aroa mountains (e.g.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] Cerro Atravesado at 1712 meters a.s.l.).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] Barquisimeto is located in central-western Venezuela, 363 km (226 mi) from Caracas, the country's capital city.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] Being a point of convergence of major road and rail routes, it has a diverse economy and has grown into a large city of 930,000 inhabitants.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] Its flat relief has enabled a systematic urban grid with streets numbered in ascending numerical order, and consistent signage that helps with locating addresses.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] Barquisimeto has an average temperature of 25 °C (77 °F) throughout the year; its driest period is from December to March.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] In the city, a hot semi-arid climate (Köppen *BSh*) is dominant.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] Located in that region, Barquisimeto records 550 millimetres or 21.7 inches of rain per year and its average temperature ranges 25 °C (77 °F).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] However, in higher regions near the Andes, temperatures are lower and the rain is more constant.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] For instance, in Sanare city, the annual average rainfall is 835 millimetres or 32.9 inches.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] Barquisimeto is a city with a historic vocation by academic knowledge, and boasts a considerable sample of universities and institutes of higher education in Venezuela, has a high and growing student population from all over the country.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] Major universities in the city include Universidad Centroccidental Lisandro Alvarado and Universidad Nacional Experimental Politécnica Antonio José de Sucre.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] The Transbarca system is a new "bus rapid transit" (BRT) system under construction, which was originally planned to use trolleybuses.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] When construction began, in 2006, the system was projected to serve an average of 170,000 people per day when completed, using 80 trolleybuses operating along 30 km (19 mi) of exclusive lanes, across the metropolitan area.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] Service was planned to include an express route of 22 km (14 mi) along with one local route of 8 km (5 mi).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] With 52 stations, the BRT system is to include a centralized system of communication and security, and structures for easy access for elderly and disabled people.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] It is to be complemented with feeder routes, covering the areas of Greater Barquisimeto the BRT line will not serve, which will connect with the main line at terminal stations.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] Although 80 articulated trolleybuses were purchased from Neoplan and delivered around 2008–09, the plans to operate the Transbarca system with those vehicles were dropped in 2013.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] In addition to reasons of cost, an inadequate supply of electricity with which to power the system was cited in the announcement of the decision.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] The city has an airport called Jacinto Lara International Airport.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] The city is home to several notable baseball and football teams.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/barquisimeto] Several other sports also have Barquisimeto as their home.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5-pan-american-championship] The **Baseball5 Pan American Championship** is the main Baseball5 tournament in the Americas, governed by WBSC Americas.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5-pan-american-championship] The top three teams qualify to the Baseball5 World Cup.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5-pan-american-championship] Mexico, a member of WBSC Americas, hosted the 2022 Baseball5 World Cup, the inaugural tournament of the Baseball5 World Cup.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5-pan-american-championship] Since there was no qualifying event for the Americas, Cuba and Venezuela were invited by the World Baseball Softball Confederation to join Mexico in the championship as the three teams representing the Americas.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5-pan-american-championship] The inaugural Baseball5 Pan American Championship was contested from 27 to 30 June 2024 in the Domo Bolivariano in Barquisimeto, Venezuela with four teams taking part: hosts Venezuela, Cuba, Mexico and Puerto Rico, who made its international debut in Baseball5 competition.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5-pan-american-championship] Cuba won the 2024 Baseball5 Pan American Championship undefeated, with a 6–0 opening round record, and beating Mexico 2 sets to 0 in the final.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5-pan-american-championship] Venezuela, that lost the semifinals against Mexico, was awarded the bronze medal.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] Outs (eliminations) occur either when a hit ball is caught before it touches the ground by a defender, or (in specific situations) when a defender with the ball either touches the base a runner is supposed to reach, or touches the runner themselves.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] Offensive players can also get themselves out by breaking the rules while hitting the ball or running the bases.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] The teams switch roles after three outs are made, with an "inning" being completed when both teams have played offense once.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] The game is played to five innings, with any ties being broken by playing extra innings as necessary, and games generally lasting 15 to 20 minutes.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] Oftentimes, a best-of-three (or even best-of-five) series of "sets" is played to determine the result of a matchup between two teams.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] Unlike baseball/softball, there is no pitcher, with the batter (offensive player who hits the ball) starting each play with the ball, which is the only equipment used in the game.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] The WBSC proposed the game in 2017 with the intention of growing baseball/softball on a global level, claiming that the game's low cost, fast pace, and small field make it a more accessible and appealing entry point to those sports.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] It organizes a mixed-gender B5 World Cup for senior and youth players in alternating years, with teams required to field at least two active players per gender.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] The game is also scheduled to be played in a mixed-gender format at the 2026 Summer Youth Olympics, and has started to find adoption in schools, national championships, and other international events around the world.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] B5 was inspired by similar games that have been played on the streets in Latin America and elsewhere for decades, such as cuatro esquinas (*four corners*) in Cuba and pelotica de goma (*little rubber ball*) in Venezuela.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] In some cases, B5 significantly diverges from the rules of these games; for example, it does not feature a pitcher, as is done in one street variation in Colombia, and players are allowed to run the bases, as opposed to only walking, as is required in one version of "cuatro esquinas".
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] Before B5, the WBSC had tried promoting several other baseball variants at a youth level, such as tee-ball, without significant success.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] B5 was invented in part to increase the odds that a sport similar to baseball and softball will be played in the Olympics, with B5 meant to contribute to an ultimate goal of having a billion fans in the baseball-softball community by 2030 and helping to demonstrate the global reach of the games.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] It also intended to create a game that would be more accessible and cheap, as the only equipment used in B5 is the rubber ball, and the field is much smaller than a baseball diamond or softball field, with the game being playable indoors.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] In this respect, as well as the fact that there are fewer players required to play a game, B5 is meant to imitate smaller, more urban variants of other major sports, such as 3x3 basketball, futsal, and rugby sevens.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] Inclusiveness is meant to be another goal of B5, with the game being scheduled to be the first mixed-gender team sport in an Olympic event to not have a separate competition for male-only or female-only teams.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] In addition, the game is meant to be simpler to learn, have more youth appeal, and be more exciting, with players participating more frequently throughout the game.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] Another claimed benefit is that with B5 being introduced across the entire world at the same time, no one country is likely to dominate the game; the lack of the pitcher role, which is highly specialized, contributes to this.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] The first Baseball5 international competition took place at Foro Italico, Italy in 2018.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] The game was demonstrated and played in various places across the world, such as in the United States during the MLB All-Star Week, in the 2021 Bulgarian Olympic Festival, and on the sidelines of the 2018 Summer Youth Olympics in Argentina and the 2020 Summer Paralympics in Japan.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] The WBSC has tried to promote B5 for socially beneficial purposes as well, by taking it to places such as Jordan's Azraq refugee camp.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] It is being implemented in many schools in some countries, like Australia and France, and is now played in 83 countries.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] In 2025, the WBSC celebrated May 5th (5/5) as "High5 for Baseball5" day.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] Before the 2022 Baseball5 World Cup, a new B5 rulebook was published that increased clarity on some of the rules, as well as changing some of the field dimensions.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] For example, the bases were increased in size from 50 cm (20 in) to 60 cm (24 in), and were moved from the inner edge of the infield to the outer edge, increasing the distance between them by 0.5 metres (1 ft 8 in).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] In 2025, a double base was added for home plate.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] The infield is a 13 m (42.65 ft)-square, with a base in every corner.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] The fair territory is a 18 m (59.06 ft)-square, with one of the corners coinciding with the home plate (the final base).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] The batter's box is a 3 m (9.84 ft)-square.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] It is placed outside of the fair territory and is built on the extension of the two foul lines (which distinguish fair and foul territory, and sit in fair territory) crossing each other at the home plate corner; the lines are included as part of the batter's box area.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] All bases are marked on the ground (i.e. they are not physical cushions like in baseball/softball).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] Ideal shape and size of the first three bases is a 60 cm (23.62 in)-square, and they are placed in the outfield (the part of fair territory outside of the infield).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] In order to avoid collisions, the first base is "doubled" in foul territory, with the outer base referred to as the "safety base".
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] Home plate also has a double base, known as the "safety plate", which can be found diagonally adjacent in the batter's box as a 90 cm (35 in) triangle.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] The ideal height of the fences bounding the field is 1 m (3.28 ft).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] However, every league or tournament organisation may decide on other ways of limiting the field of play, such as using existing walls or marking the ground with lines.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] The only piece of equipment used is a hollow rubber ball with a circumference of 208.4 mm (8.20 in).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] The Visitor team starts the game in offense, with the Home team on defense.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] The goal of the offensive team is to have each of its players hit the ball and then run counterclockwise around all four bases in order without being eliminated by the defense, thus scoring one run for their team.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] The act of hitting takes place while a hitter is entirely in the batter's box; the hitter must not step out of the lines until the hit ball reaches fair territory, and must first signal which hand they will hit with.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] If these requirements are not met, or if the ball goes into foul territory before passing first or third base, then the batter is out.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] The batter in the action of running towards first base, after putting the ball in play, has to touch the base in foul territory (the "safety base") except in circumstances where a collision could be avoided by going toward the base in fair territory.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] A runner (offensive player) who touches first base, second base, third base and home plate in that order scores one run for their team, and then leaves the field until their next turn as a hitter.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] When scoring, a runner must step on the safety plate rather than home plate, which is reserved for the defenders in order to avoid collisions.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] Note: If a play occurs where the batter failed to legally hit the ball, then the play is canceled (i.e. any runners who got out or advanced around the bases during the play return to their bases as if the play never happened) and the batter is eliminated.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] In teams with only five players, the first player "called out" (eliminated) in that inning becomes pinch runner on the base of the runner who is required to hit.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] The batting order and the gender balance (in mixed-gender competitions) shall always be respected.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] The five players (1st Base, 2nd Base, Midfielder, Shortstop, and 3rd Base, from right to left) of the defensive team shall all be in fair territory when the batter hits the ball.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] The ball remains live if a defender with the ball leaves the field, so long as they secured possession of the ball in fair territory.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] If the ball leaves the court due to a defensive error (missed throw or missed catch of a thrown ball), each runner is awarded an extra base (i.e. the batter goes to 2nd base, and all other runners advance 2 bases as well).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] Any runner who clearly advanced 2 bases before the defensive error may be granted an extra base as well (i.e. a runner on 1st who advanced to 3rd before the error can be awarded home plate).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] The game ends at the end of the fifth inning if one team has scored more runs than the opponent.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] Should the Home Team be ahead on the score after the Guest Team has completed its fifth offensive inning, the game is over and the Home Team wins.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] Many B5 tournaments feature best-of-three series known as "matches" or "games", with each individual game in the series called a "game" or "set", and the team winning two sets being the winner of the overall match.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] In case of a tie game, the teams shall play and complete extra inning(s) until one team scores more runs than the opponent.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] In the sixth inning, the player scheduled to hit fifth (i.e. the player who batted last in the fifth inning, and whose name precedes the first batter of the sixth inning) is placed on first base as a runner to start the inning.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] In the seventh inning, the players scheduled to hit fifth and fourth are placed on first and second base respectively, and so on with three runners to start the following innings until the game ends.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] By WBSC regulations, the game ends if there is still a tie after 7 extra innings.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] A game is over if a team leads by 15 runs at the end of the third inning or by 10 at the end of the fourth.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] At the international level, B5 is administered by the World Baseball Softball Confederation (WBSC).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] Within each country, it is administered by the national baseball and/or softball governing body.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] Exceptions apply for certain countries, such as Japan, where a specific governing body has been set up to run B5.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] The Baseball5 World Cup (B5WC) and Youth Baseball5 World Cup (YB5WC) are administered by the WBSC, with both tournaments alternating and happening every two years, and following the general format of having 50 games played between 12 national teams over 7 days.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] Continental qualifiers for each tournament will be played during their off-year.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/baseball5] The 2025 YB5WC will act as a qualifier for the mixed-gender Baseball5 event to be held in the Dakar 2026 Youth Olympic Games (YOG).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-national-baseball5-team] The **Cuba national Baseball5 team** represents Cuba in international Baseball5 competitions.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-national-baseball5-team] They are the current World and Pan American Champions.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-national-baseball5-team] Baseball5 was inspired by similar games that have been played on the streets in Latin America and elsewhere for decades, such as "cuatro esquinas" (*four corners*) in Cuba.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-national-baseball5-team] Cuba, alongside Venezuela, were invited by the World Baseball Softball Confederation to represent WBSC Americas in the 2022 Baseball5 World Cup, held in Mexico City.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-national-baseball5-team] The Cuban team finished the tournament undefeated and won the final against Japan 2 matches to 0.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-national-baseball5-team] Briandy Molina was honored with the Outstanding Male Player Award and included in the All Star Team of the tournament.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-national-baseball5-team] Cuba won the 2024 Baseball5 Pan American Championship held in Barquisimeto, Venezuela.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-national-baseball5-team] The Cuban squad finished undefeated with a 6–0 record and defeated Mexico in the final 2 sets to 0, qualifying to the 2024 Baseball5 World Cup.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-national-baseball5-team] Briandy Molina and Chaquira Azpiazu were awarded as the Most Valuable Players of the tournament, while manager Pablo Terry won the Best Coach Award.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuba was inhabited as early as the 4th millennium BC, with the Guanahatabey and Taíno peoples present at the time of Spanish colonization in the 15th century.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuba's population descends primarily from three groups: pre-Columbian indigenous peoples, chiefly the Taíno and Ciboney, Spanish settlers and immigrants (mainly from Andalusia, the Canary Islands, Galicia, and Asturias), and sub-Saharan Africans brought through the transatlantic slave trade.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The territory remained part of the Spanish Empire until the Spanish–American War of 1898, after which it was occupied by the United States and gained independence in 1902.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] A 1933 coup toppled the democratically elected government of Carlos Manuel de Céspedes y Quesada and began a long period of military influence, particularly by Fulgencio Batista.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 1940, Cuba implemented a new constitution, but mounting political unrest culminated in the 1952 Cuban coup d'état by Batista.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] His autocratic government was overthrown in January 1959 by the 26th of July Movement during the Cuban Revolution.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] That revolution established communist rule under the leadership of Fidel Castro.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The country under Castro was a point of contention during the Cold War between the Soviet Union and the United States, and the Cuban Missile Crisis of 1962 is widely considered the closest the Cold War came to escalating into nuclear war.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] During the 1970s through the late 1980s, Cuba intervened in numerous conflicts in support of anti-colonial and Marxist governments or movements across Africa, Latin America, and the Middle East.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] According to a CIA declassified report, Cuba had received $33 billion in Soviet aid by 1984.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Following the dissolution of the Soviet Union, Cuba faced a severe economic downturn in the 1990s, known as the Special Period.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 2008, Castro retired after 49 years; Raúl Castro was elected his successor.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Raúl retired as president of the Council of State in 2018, and Miguel Díaz-Canel was elected president by the National Assembly following parliamentary elections.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Raúl retired as First Secretary of the Communist Party in 2021, and Díaz-Canel was elected thereafter, becoming Cuba's first leader to have been born after the Cuban Revolution.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuba is a socialist state in which the role of the Communist Party is enshrined in the Constitution.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuba is currently the world's only communist country outside of Asia.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuba has an authoritarian government wherein political opposition is prohibited.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Censorship is extensive, and independent journalism is repressed; Reporters Without Borders has characterized Cuba as one of the worst countries for press freedom.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuba is a founding member of the UN, G77, NAM, OACPS, ALBA, and OAS.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Since 1959, Cuba has regarded the U.S. military presence in Guantánamo Bay as illegal.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuba has one of the world's few command economies, and its economy is dominated by tourism and the exports of skilled labor, sugar, tobacco, and coffee.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuba has historically—before and during communist rule—performed better than other countries in Latin America and the Caribbean in literacy.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] After the 1959 revolution, Cuba performed better than other Latin American countries in infant and maternal mortality, and life expectancy.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] According to a 2012 study, Cuba is the only country in the world to meet the conditions of sustainable development put forth by the WWF.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuba has a universal health care system that provides free medical treatment to all Cuban citizens, although challenges include low salaries for doctors, poor facilities, poor provision of equipment, and the frequent absence of essential drugs.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] A 2023 study by the Cuban Observatory of Human Rights estimated that 88% of the population lives in extreme poverty.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] According to the World Food Programme of the United Nations, rationed food meets only a fraction of daily nutritional needs for many Cubans, leading to health issues.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Ongoing since 1960, the United States embargo against Cuba stands as one of the longest-running trade and economic measures in bilateral relations in history.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Historians believe the name *Cuba* comes from the Taíno language; however, its derivation is unknown.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] *Cuba* may be translated either as 'where fertile land is abundant' (*cubao*), or 'great place' (*coabana*).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Another hypothesis on the name's origin is that the island was named after the town of Cuba, Portugal, supported by those who believe that Christopher Columbus was Portuguese.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Humans first settled Cuba around 6,000 years ago, descending from migrations from northern South America or Central America.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The arrival of humans on Cuba is associated with extinctions of the island's native fauna, particularly its endemic sloths.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The Arawakan-speaking ancestors of the Taíno people arrived in the Caribbean in a separate migration from South America around 1,700 years ago.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Recent archaeogenetic evidence indicates that this expansion largely replaced the earlier pre-ceramic populations of the island with almost no genetic admixture between the groups.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Unlike the previous settlers of Cuba, the Taíno extensively produced pottery and engaged in intensive agriculture.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The earliest evidence of the Taíno people on Cuba dates to the 9th century.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Descendants of the first settlers of Cuba persisted on the western part of the island until Columbian contact, where they were recorded as the Guanahatabey people, who lived a hunter-gatherer lifestyle.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Christopher Columbus arrived in Cuba on October 27, 1492, and landed the following day.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Columbus claimed the island for the new Kingdom of Spain and named it *Isla Juana* ("John's Island") after John, Prince of Asturias.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 1511 the first Spanish settlement was founded by Diego Velázquez de Cuéllar at Baracoa.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Other settlements followed, including San Cristobal de la Habana, founded in 1514 (southern coast of the island) and then in 1519 (current place), which later became the capital (1607).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The Taíno were forced to work under the *encomienda* system, which resembled the feudal system in medieval Europe.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Within a century, the Taíno faced high incidence of mortality from multiple factors—primarily Eurasian infectious diseases to which they had no acquired immunity, aggravated by the harsh conditions of the repressive colonial subjugation.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 1529, a measles outbreak killed two-thirds of those few indigenous individuals who had previously survived smallpox.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] On 18 May 1539, conquistador Hernando de Soto departed from Havana with some 600 followers on an extensive expedition through the Southeastern United States in search of gold, treasure, fame, and power.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] On 1 September 1548, Gonzalo Perez de Angulo was appointed governor of Cuba.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] He arrived in Santiago de Cuba on 4 November 1549 and declared the liberty of the indigenous population.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] He became Cuba's first permanent governor, residing in Havana, and he built the first church made of masonry in Cuba.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] By 1570, most residents of Cuba had a mixture of Spanish, African, and Taíno heritages.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuba developed slowly and, unlike the plantation islands of the Caribbean, had a diversified agriculture.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Most importantly, the colony developed as an urbanized society that primarily supported the Spanish colonial empire.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] By the mid-18th century, there were 50,000 slaves on the island.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Estimates suggest that between 1790 and 1820, some 325,000 Africans were imported to Cuba as slaves, which was four times the amount that had arrived between 1760 and 1790.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 1812, the Aponte slave rebellion took place, but it was ultimately suppressed.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] By the 19th century, the practice of *coartacion* had developed (or "buying oneself out of slavery", a "uniquely Cuban development").
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] With a shortage of white labor, blacks dominated urban industries to such an extent that when whites in large numbers came to Cuba in the middle of the 19th century, they were unable to displace black workers.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] A system of diversified agriculture, with small farms and fewer slaves, served to supply the cities with produce and other goods.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In the 1820s, when the rest of Spain's empire in Latin America rebelled and formed independent states, Cuba remained loyal to Spain.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Its economy was based on serving the empire.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Full independence from Spain was the goal of a rebellion in 1868 led by planter Carlos Manuel de Céspedes.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] De Céspedes, a sugar planter, freed his slaves to fight with him for an independent Cuba.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] On 27 December 1868, he issued a decree condemning slavery in theory—but accepting it in practice—and declaring free any slaves whose masters presented them for military service.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The 1868 rebellion resulted in a prolonged conflict known as the Ten Years' War.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The Cuban rebels were joined by former Dominican colonial officers, volunteers from Canada, Colombia, France, Mexico, the United States, and Chinese indentured servants, but lacked support from wealthy planters and the majority of slaves.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Céspedes was killed by Spanish troops in 1874.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The United States declined to recognize the new Cuban government, although many European and Latin American nations did.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 1878, the Pact of Zanjón ended the conflict, with Spain promising greater autonomy to Cuba.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 1879–80, Cuban patriot Calixto García attempted to start another war known as the Little War but failed to receive enough support.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Slavery in Cuba was abolished in 1875, with the process completed by 1886.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Exiled dissident José Martí founded the Cuban Revolutionary Party in New York City in 1892.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The party aimed to achieve Cuban independence from Spain.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 1895, he traveled to San Fernando de Monte Cristi and Santo Domingo in the Dominican Republic to join the efforts of Máximo Gómez.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] He recorded his political views in the *Manifesto of Montecristi*.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Fighting against the Spanish army began in Cuba on 24 February 1895, and Martí arrived in April.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] He was killed in the Battle of Dos Rios on 19 May 1895.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] His death immortalized him as Cuba's national hero.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Around 200,000 Spanish troops outnumbered the much smaller rebel army, which relied mostly on guerrilla and sabotage tactics.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The Spaniards began a campaign of suppression.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] General Valeriano Weyler, the military governor of Cuba, herded the rural population into what he called *reconcentrados*, described by international observers as "fortified towns".
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] These are often considered the prototype for 20th-century concentration camps.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Between 200,000 and 400,000 Cuban civilians died from starvation and disease in the Spanish concentration camps, numbers verified by the Red Cross and United States Senator Redfield Proctor, a former Secretary of War.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] American and European protests against Spanish conduct on the island followed.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The U.S. battleship USS *Maine* was sent to protect American interests, but soon after its arrival, it exploded in the Havana Harbor and sank quickly, killing nearly three-quarters of the crew.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The cause and responsibility for the ship's sinking remained unclear after a board of inquiry.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Popular opinion in the U.S., fueled by active yellow press, concluded that the Spanish were to blame and demanded action.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Spain and the United States declared war on each other in late April 1898.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Under Cuba's constitution, the United States retained the right to intervene in Cuban affairs and to supervise its finances and foreign relations.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Under the Platt Amendment, the U.S. leased the Guantánamo Bay Naval Base from Cuba.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Following disputed elections in 1906, the first president, Tomás Estrada Palma, faced an armed revolt by independence war veterans who defeated the meager government forces.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The U.S. intervened by occupying Cuba and named Charles Edward Magoon as governor for three years.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuban historians have characterized Magoon's governorship as introducing political and social corruption.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 1908, self-government was restored when José Miguel Gómez was elected president, but the U.S. continued intervening in Cuban affairs.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 1912, the Partido Independiente de Color attempted to establish a separate black republic in Oriente Province, but was suppressed by General Monteagudo with considerable bloodshed.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 1924, Gerardo Machado was elected president.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] During his administration, tourism increased markedly, and American-owned hotels and restaurants were built to accommodate the influx of tourists.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The tourist boom led to increases in gambling and prostitution in Cuba.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The Wall Street crash of 1929 led to a collapse in the price of sugar, political unrest, and repression.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Protesting students, known as the Generation of 1930, turned to violence in opposition to the increasingly unpopular Machado.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] A general strike (in which the Communist Party sided with Machado), uprisings among sugar workers, and an army revolt forced Machado into exile in August 1933.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] He was replaced by Carlos Manuel de Céspedes y Quesada, son of the revolutionary hero Carlos Manuel de Céspedes.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In September 1933 the Sergeants' Revolt, led by Sergeant Fulgencio Batista, overthrew Céspedes.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] A five-member executive committee (the Pentarchy of 1933) was chosen to head a provisional government.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Ramón Grau San Martín was appointed as provisional president.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Grau resigned in 1934, leaving the way clear for Batista, who dominated Cuban politics for the next 25 years, at first through a series of puppet presidents.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The period from 1933 to 1937 was a time of "virtually unremitting social and political warfare".
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] On balance, during the period 1933–1940, Cuba suffered from fragile political structures, with three presidents in two years (1935–1936) and in the militaristic and repressive policies of Batista as head of the army.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The 1940 Constitution of Cuba engineered radically progressive ideas, including the right to labor and right to health care.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Batista was elected president in the same year, holding the post until 1944.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] He is, as of 2004, the only non-white Cuban to win the nation's highest political office.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] His government carried out major social reforms.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Several members of the Communist Party held office under his administration.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuban armed forces were not greatly involved in combat during World War II—though Batista did suggest a joint U.S.-Latin American assault on Francoist Spain to overthrow its authoritarian regime.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuba lost six merchant ships during the war, and the Cuban Navy was credited with sinking the German submarine *U-176*.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Batista adhered to the 1940 constitution's strictures preventing his re-election.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Grau further corroded the base of the already teetering legitimacy of the political system, particularly by undermining the Congress and Supreme Court.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Carlos Prío Socarrás, a protégé of Grau, became president in 1948.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The two terms of the Partido Auténtico brought an influx of investment, which fueled an economic boom, raised living standards for all segments of society, and created a middle class in most urban areas.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] After finishing his term in 1944, Batista lived in Florida, returning to Cuba to run for president in 1952.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Facing inevitable electoral defeat, he led a military coup that preempted the election.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Back in power and receiving financial, military, and logistical support from the United States government, Batista suspended the 1940 constitution and revoked most political liberties, including the right to strike.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] He then aligned with landowners who owned the largest sugar plantations, and presided over a stagnating economy that widened the gap between rich and poor Cubans.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Batista outlawed the Cuban Communist Party in 1952.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] After the coup, Cuba had Latin America's highest per capita consumption rates of meat, vegetables, cereals, automobiles, telephones and radios, though about one-third of the population was considered poor and enjoyed relatively little of this consumption.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] However, in his "History Will Absolve Me" speech, Fidel Castro mentioned that national issues relating to land, industrialization, housing, unemployment, education, and health were contemporary problems.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 1958 Cuba was a well-advanced country compared to other Latin American regions, but it was affected by perhaps Latin America's largest labor union privileges, including bans on dismissals and mechanization.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] They were obtained in large measure "at the cost of the unemployed and the peasants", leading to disparities.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Between 1933 and 1958, Cuba extended economic regulations enormously, causing economic problems.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Unemployment became a problem as graduates entering the workforce could not find jobs.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The middle class became increasingly dissatisfied with unemployment and political persecution.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The labor unions, manipulated by the previous government since 1948 through union "yellowness", supported Batista.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In the 1950s, various organizations, including some advocating armed uprising, competed for public support in bringing about political change.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 1956, Castro and about 80 supporters landed from the yacht *Granma* in an attempt to start a rebellion against the Batista government.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 1958, Castro's 26th of July Movement emerged as the leading revolutionary group.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The U.S. supported Castro by imposing a 1958 arms embargo against Batista's government.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Batista evaded the American embargo and acquired weapons from the Dominican Republic.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] By late 1958, the rebels had broken out of the Sierra Maestra and launched a general popular insurrection.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] After Castro's fighters captured Santa Clara, Batista fled to the Dominican Republic on 1 January 1959 with his family, going into exile in Portugal.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Castro's forces entered the capital on 8 January.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The liberal Manuel Urrutia Lleó became the provisional president.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Before the revolution, U.S. and other foreign investors dominated the Cuban economy, controlling 75% of arable land, 90% of essential services, and 40% of sugar production.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] One of the goals of Castro's revolution was to achieve economic independence, but Cuba instead became heavily dependent on Soviet subsidies, with additional economic aid provided by Eastern European countries through COMECON.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The US government initially reacted favorably to the Cuban Revolution, seeing it as part of a movement to bring democracy to Latin America.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Castro's legalization of the Communist Party and the hundreds of executions of Batista agents, policemen, and soldiers that followed caused a deterioration in the relationship between the two countries.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The promulgation of the Agrarian Reform Law, expropriating thousands of acres of farmland (including from large U.S. landholders), further worsened relations.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In response, between 1960 and 1964 the U.S. imposed a range of sanctions, eventually including a total ban on trade between the countries and a freeze on all Cuban-owned assets in the U.S.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In February 1960, Castro signed a commercial agreement with Soviet Vice-Premier Anastas Mikoyan.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Eisenhower gave his approval to a CIA plan to arm and train a group of Cuban refugees to overthrow the Castro government.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The CIA provided B-26 light bombers and ships to the rebels for the invasion.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] On 15 April 1961 at dawn, Brigade 2506 flew from Puerto Cabezas, Nicaragua, and carried out preemptive airstrikes on Cuban military airfields at San Antonio de Los Baños, Ciudad Libertad, Pinar del Río, and Santiago de Cuba, destroying five aircraft and damaging an indeterminable number.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The invasion (known as the Bay of Pigs Invasion) took place on 17 April, during the term of President John F.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] About 1,400 Cuban exiles disembarked at the Bay of Pigs.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuban troops and local militias defeated the invasion by 19 April, killing over 100 invaders and taking the remainder prisoner.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Five B-26s were shot down by the Cuban air force, and one was downed by anti-aircraft fire.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In January 1962, Cuba was suspended from the Organization of American States (OAS), and imposed sanctions of similar nature to the U.S. sanctions.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The failed amphibious assault on Cuba contributed to the Soviet decision to deploy R-12 missiles there, and the ensuing Cuban Missile Crisis of October 1962 almost sparked World War III.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 1962, American generals proposed Operation Northwoods which would entail committing terrorist attacks in American cities and against refugees and falsely blaming the attacks on the Cuban government, manufacturing a reason for the United States to invade Cuba.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] By 1963, Cuba was moving towards a full-fledged communist state system modeled on the USSR.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Eloy Gutiérrez Menoyo founded the anti-Castro group Alpha 66 in the early 1960s, which used small craft to attack Cuban and Soviet merchant ships, killing or wounding crew members.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 1964, Menoyo set up a guerrilla training camp in the Dominican Republic, and after entering Cuba in 1965, he was captured; however, Alpha 66 continued its raids under new leadership.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] By the mid-1960s, Soviet aid had strengthened the Cuban air force and navy, making raids costly without significant U.S. support.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuba provided support to revolutions throughout Africa and Latin America.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 1963, Cuba sent 686 troops together with 22 tanks and other military equipment to support Algeria in the Sand War against Morocco.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The Cuban forces remained in Algeria for over a year, providing training to the Algerian army.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Che Guevara, authorized by Castro, engaged in guerrilla activities in Africa and was killed in 1967 while attempting to start a revolution in Bolivia.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuba supplied arms to the People's Movement for the Liberation of Angola; gave aid to the African Party for the Independence of Guinea and Cape Verde; and provided military training to the Mozambique Liberation Front.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuban troops prevented the 1966 Republic of the Congo coup attempt; the coup collapsed when the Congolese army refused to engage in combat against the Cubans.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuban advisors began operating with guerrillas in the Guinea-Bissau War of Independence, and in November 1969 Portuguese troops captured Cuban Captain Pedro Rodriguez Peralta.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Starting in 1968, a campaign titled the "revolutionary offensive" was initiated to nationalize some 58,000 remaining private small businesses.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The campaign would spur industrialization in Cuba and focus the economy on sugar production, with a goal of 10 million tons by 1970.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The economic focus on sugar production involved international volunteers and the mobilization of workers from all sectors of the economy.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Economic mobilization coincided with greater militarization of political structures and society in general.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The economy fell into decline after large sectors were neglected after urban labor was mobilized to the countryside.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The standard of living in the 1970s was "extremely spartan," and discontent was rife.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Castro admitted the failures of economic policies in a 1970 speech.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 1975, the OAS lifted its sanctions against Cuba with the approval of 16 member states, including the United States.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The U.S., however, maintained its own sanctions.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] According to Amnesty International, official death sentences from 1959 to 1987 numbered 237, of which all but 21 were carried out.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The vast majority of those executed directly following the 1959 Revolution were policemen, politicians, and informers of the Batista regime accused of crimes such as torture and murder, and their public trials and executions had widespread popular support among the Cuban population.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] During the Cold War, Cuba received $33 billion in Soviet aid, and Cuban forces were deployed to all corners of Africa, either as military advisors or as combatants.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Soviet pilots and technicians assumed defense duties in Cuba, freeing up personnel to be deployed in Africa.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 1979, the U.S. objected to the presence of Soviet combat troops on the island.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In November 1975, Cuba deployed more than 65,000 troops and 400 Soviet-made tanks in Angola in one of the fastest military mobilizations in history.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] South Africa developed nuclear weapons because of the threat to its security posed by the presence of large numbers of Cuban troops in Angola.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 1975–76 and again in 1988 at the Battle of Cuito Cuanavale, the Cubans alongside their MPLA allies fought UNITA rebels and apartheid South African forces.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In December 1977, Cuba sent its combat troops from Angola, the People's Republic of the Congo, and the Caribbean to Ethiopia, assisted by mechanized Soviet battalions, to help defeat a Somali invasion.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] On 24 January 1978, Ethiopian and Cuban troops counterattacked, inflicting 3,000 casualties on the Somali forces.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In February, Cuban troops launched a major offensive and forced the Somali army back into its own territory.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuban forces remained in Ethiopia until September 1989.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Despite its small size and the long distance separating it from the Middle East, Cuba played an active role in the region during the Cold War.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 1972, a major military mission consisting of tank, air, and artillery specialists was dispatched to South Yemen.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuban military advisors were sent to Iraq in the mid-1970s, but their mission was canceled after Iraq invaded Iran in 1980.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The Cubans were also involved in the Syrian-Israeli conflict in 1973 and 1974 that followed the Yom Kippur War.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Israeli sources reported the presence of a Cuban tank brigade in the Golan Heights, which was supported by two brigades.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Tank forces engaged in battle on the Golan front.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] After the U.S. was defeated by communist forces in the Vietnam War, Castro began supporting Marxist insurgencies in Guatemala, El Salvador, Nicaragua, and Colombia by supplying weapons, munitions, and training.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Following the 1983 coup that resulted in the execution of Grenadian Prime Minister Maurice Bishop and establishment of the military government led by Hudson Austin, U.S. forces invaded Grenada in 1983, overthrowing the pro-Castro government.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In a few days of fighting, 6,000 American combat troops defeated 784 Cubans (636 construction workers with military training, 43 military advisors, and 18 diplomats).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuba gradually withdrew its troops from Angola in 1989–91.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] An important psychological and political aspect of the Cuban military involvement in Africa was the significant presence of black or mixed-race soldiers among the Cuban forces.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] According to one source, more than 300,000 Cuban military personnel and civilian experts were deployed in Africa.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The source also states that out of the 50,000 Cubans sent to Angola, half contracted AIDS, and that 10,000 Cubans died as a consequence of their military actions in Africa.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Soviet troops began to withdraw from Cuba in September 1991, and Castro's rule was severely tested in the aftermath of the Soviet collapse in December 1991 (known in Cuba as the Special Period).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The country faced a severe economic downturn following the withdrawal of Soviet subsidies worth $4 billion to $6 billion annually, resulting in effects such as food and fuel shortages.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The government did not accept American donations of food, medicines and cash until 1993.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] On 5 August 1994, state security dispersed protesters in a spontaneous protest in Havana.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] From the start of the crisis until 1995, Cuba saw its gross domestic product (GDP) shrink by 35%.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] It took another five years for its GDP to reach pre-crisis levels.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 1996, after Cuban fighter jets shot down two small aircraft piloted by a Florida-based anti-Castro group, the U.S.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Congress passed the Helms–Burton Act, strengthening U.S. embargoes.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuba then found a new source of aid and support in the People's Republic of China.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In addition, Castro, Venezuelan President Hugo Chávez and Bolivian President Evo Morales became allies, and both countries began to support the Cuban economy.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 2003, the government arrested and imprisoned a large number of civil activists, a period known as the "Black Spring".
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In February 2008, Castro resigned as President of the State Council due to illness.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] On 24 February, the National Assembly elected his brother Raúl Castro as president.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In his inauguration speech, Raúl promised that some of the restrictions on freedom in Cuba would be removed.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In March 2009, Raúl Castro removed some of his brother's appointees.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 2009 the OAS adopted a resolution to end the 47-year ban on Cuban membership of the group.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The resolution stated, however, that full membership would be delayed until Cuba was "in conformity with the practices, purposes, and principles of the OAS".
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Fidel Castro wrote that Cuba would not rejoin the OAS, which he said was a "U.S.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Trojan horse" and "complicit" in actions taken by the U.S. against Cuba and other Latin American nations.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 2013 Cuba ended the requirement established in 1961 that any citizens who wished to travel abroad were required to obtain an expensive government permit and a letter of invitation.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In 1961 the Cuban government had imposed broad restrictions on travel to prevent the mass emigration of people after the 1959 revolution; it approved exit visas only on rare occasions.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In the first year of the program, over 180,000 left Cuba and returned.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Talks with American officials, including President Barack Obama, resulted in the 2014 release of Alan Gross, 52 political prisoners, and an unnamed non-citizen agent of the United States in return for the release of three Cubans who had been convicted of espionage in the United States.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The embargo between the United States and Cuba was relaxed to allow import, export, and certain limited commerce.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Raúl Castro stepped down from the presidency in 2018, and Miguel Díaz-Canel was elected president of the State Council by the National Assembly following parliamentary elections.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Raúl Castro remained the First Secretary of the Communist Party and retained broad authority, including oversight over the president.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuba approved a new constitution in 2019.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The optional vote attracted 84.4% of eligible voters; 90% of those who voted approved the constitution, and 9% opposed it.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Any form of discrimination harmful to human dignity is banned under the constitution.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] President Donald Trump added Cuba to the State Sponsors of Terrorism list, implementing a series of additional economic sanctions on the country.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Díaz-Canel succeeded Castro as first secretary of the Communist Party.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In July 2021, there were several large protests against the government under the banner of Patria y Vida.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuban exiles also conducted protests overseas.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The song associated with the movement received international acclaim including a Latin Grammy Award.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The 2024–2026 Cuba blackouts were the most severe living crisis that the country has experienced since the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Díaz-Canel blamed the blackout on the United States embargo against Cuba, which he said prevented much needed supplies and replacement parts from reaching Cuba.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuba is an archipelago of 4,195 islands, cays and islets located in the northern Caribbean Sea at the convergence of the Gulf of Mexico and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] It lies between latitudes 19° and 24°N, and longitudes 74° and 85°W.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Key West, Florida, is about 150 km (93 miles) across the Straits of Florida to the north and northwest, and The Bahamas (Cay Lobos) 22.5 km (14 mi) to the north.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Mexico lies 210 km (130.5 mi) west across the Yucatán Channel (to the closest tip of Cabo Catoche).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Haiti is 78 km (48.5 mi) east and Jamaica 148 km (92 mi) south.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The main island, named Cuba, is 1,250 km (780 mi) long, constituting most of the nation's land area (104,338 km2 or 40,285 sq mi) and is the largest island in the Caribbean and 17th-largest island in the world.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The main island consists mostly of flat to rolling plains apart from the Sierra Maestra mountains in the southeast, whose highest point is Pico Turquino (1,974 m or 6,476 ft).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The second-largest island is Isla de la Juventud in the Canarreos Archipelago, with an area of 2,204 km2 (851 sq mi).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] With the entire island south of the Tropic of Cancer, the local climate is tropical, moderated by northeasterly trade winds that blow year-round.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The temperature is also shaped by the Caribbean Current which brings in warm water from the Equator.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] This makes the climate of Cuba warmer than that of Hong Kong, which is at around the same latitude as Cuba but has a subtropical rather than a tropical climate.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] In general (with local variations), there is a drier season from November to April, and a rainier season from May to October.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The average temperature is 21 °C (70 °F) in January and 27 °C (81 °F) in July.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The warm temperatures of the Caribbean Sea and the fact that Cuba sits across the entrance to the Gulf of Mexico combine to make the country prone to frequent hurricanes.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] These are most common in September and October.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Climate change is causing an increase in temperature, rising sea levels and shifting precipitation patterns, with an overall decrease in rainfall predicted.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] These will severely impact industries key to the economy, including agriculture, forestry and tourism.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] As rainfall is Cuba's only water source, water security is an issue.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Warmer temperatures may affect the health of the population, causing an increase in cardiovascular, respiratory and viral diseases.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] A temperature rise of 2 °C above preindustrial levels can increase the likelihood of extreme hurricane rainfall by three times in Cuba.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Climate change mitigation and adaptation plans include renewable energy generation and nature-based solutions, such as restoring mangrove ecosystems.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Hurricane Irma hit the island on 8 September 2017, with winds of 260 km/h (160 mph), at the Camagüey Archipelago.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The worst damage was in the keys north of the main island.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Hospitals, warehouses and factories were damaged; much of the north coast was without electricity.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Nearly one million people, including tourists, were evacuated.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The Varadero resort area reported widespread damage.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Ten people were killed during the storm, including seven in Havana, most during building collapses.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Sections of the capital had been flooded.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuba contains six terrestrial ecoregions: Cuban moist forests, Cuban dry forests, Cuban pine forests, Cuban wetlands, Cuban cactus scrub, and Greater Antilles mangroves.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] It had a 2019 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 5.4/10, ranking it 102nd globally out of 172 countries.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Cuba signed the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) in 1992.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] A National Biodiversity Strategy and Action Plan was submitted in 2008.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The report contains a detailed breakdown of the numbers of species recorded from Cuba, the main groups being: animals (17,801 species), bacteria (270), chromista (707), fungi, including lichen-forming species (5,844), plants (9,107) and protozoa (1,440).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The native bee hummingbird or *zunzuncito* is the world's smallest known bird, with a length of 55 mm (2+1⁄8 in).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] The Cuban trogon or *tocororo* is the national bird of Cuba and an endemic species.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] Other endemic species are the Cuban crocodile, Cuban hutia, Cuban solenodon, Cuban gar, Cuban boa, and Polymita picta.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p01] *Hedychium coronarium*, named *mariposa* in Cuba, is the national flower.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The Republic of Cuba is a unitary one-party socialist state that adheres to the ideology of Marxism–Leninism.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The Constitution of 1976, which defines Cuba as a socialist republic, was amended in 1992 and 2002, and is "guided by the ideas of José Martí and the political and social ideas of Marx, Engels and Lenin".
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The constitution describes the Communist Party of Cuba as the "leading force of society and of the state".
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The political system reflects the Marxist–Leninist concept of democratic centralism.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The First Secretary of the Communist Party of Cuba is the most senior position in the one-party state.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The First Secretary leads the Politburo and the Secretariat, making the office holder the most powerful person in government.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Members of both councils are elected by the National Assembly of People's Power.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The President of Cuba, who is elected by the Assembly, serves for five years and since the ratification of the 2019 Constitution, there is a limit of two consecutive five-year terms.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The People's Supreme Court serves as the highest judicial branch of government.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] It is also the court of last resort for all appeals against the decisions of provincial courts.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba's national legislature, the National Assembly of People's Power (*Asamblea Nacional de Poder Popular*), is the supreme state organ of power; 470 members serve five-year terms.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The assembly meets twice a year; between sessions legislative power is held by the 31 member Council of Ministers.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Candidates for the Assembly are approved by public referendum.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] All Cuban citizens over 16 who have not been convicted of a criminal offense can vote.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Article 131 of the constitution states that voting shall be "through free, equal and secret vote".
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Article 136 states: "In order for deputies or delegates to be considered elected they must get more than half the number of valid votes cast in the electoral districts".
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Elections in Cuba are not considered democratic.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In elections for the National Assembly of People's Power there is only one candidate for each seat, which prevents electoral competition.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] No political party is permitted to nominate candidates or campaign on the island.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Candidates are nominated by committees that are firmly controlled by the Communist Party.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Voters can select individual candidates on their ballot, select every candidate, or leave every question blank, with no option to vote against candidates.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The Communist Party of Cuba holds Congress of the Communist Party of Cuba meetings once in around 5 years since 1975.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In 2011, the party stated that there were 800,000 members.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Party representatives generally constitute at least half of the Councils of state and the National Assembly.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The remaining positions are filled by candidates nominally without party affiliation.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Other political parties campaign and raise finances internationally, while activity by political opposition groups is minimal.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] According to International Institute for Democracy and Electoral Assistance, Cuba performs poorly on overall democratic measures.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba is considered an authoritarian regime according to The Economist's *Democracy Index*, *Freedom in the World* reports, and V-Dem Democracy Indices.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Miguel Díaz-Canel was elected president on 18 April 2018 after the resignation of Raúl Castro.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] On 19 April 2021, Díaz-Canel became First Secretary of the Communist Party.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] He is the first non-Castro to be in such top position since the Cuban Revolution of 1959.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The country is subdivided into 15 provinces and one special municipality (Isla de la Juventud).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] These were formerly part of six larger historical provinces: Pinar del Río, Habana, Matanzas, Las Villas, Camagüey and Oriente.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The present subdivisions closely resemble those of the Spanish military provinces during the Cuban Wars of Independence, when the most troublesome areas were subdivided.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The provinces are divided into municipalities.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba is a founding member of the United Nations, G77, Non-Aligned Movement, Organisation of African, Caribbean and Pacific States, ALBA, and Organization of American States.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba has conducted a foreign policy that is uncharacteristic of such a minor, developing country.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Under Castro, Cuba was heavily involved in wars in Africa, Central America and Asia.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba supported Algeria in 1961–1965 and sent tens of thousands of troops to Angola during the Angolan Civil War.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Other countries that featured Cuban involvement include Ethiopia, Guinea, Guinea-Bissau, Mozambique, and Yemen.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Lesser known actions include the 1959 missions to the Dominican Republic.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The expedition failed, but a prominent monument to its members was erected in their memory in Santo Domingo by the Dominican government, and they feature prominently at the country's Memorial Museum of the Resistance.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In 2008, the European Union and Cuba agreed to resume full relations and cooperation activities.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba is a founding member of the Bolivarian Alliance for the Americas.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Tens of thousands of Cuban medical personnel have worked abroad, with as many as 30,000 doctors in Venezuela alone via the two countries' oil-for-doctors programme.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In the wake of the Russian invasion of Ukraine and the ongoing international isolation of Russia, Cuba emerged as one of the few countries that maintained friendly relations with the Russian Federation.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Diaz-Canel visited Vladimir Putin in Moscow in November 2022, where the two leaders opened a monument of Fidel Castro, as well as speaking out against U.S. sanctions against Russia and Cuba.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Since 1960, the U.S. embargo on Cuba stands as one of the longest-running trade and economic measures in bilateral relations history, having endured for over six decades.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] This action was initiated in response to a wave of nationalizations that impacted American properties valued at over US$1 billion.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] This measure was intensified in 1962 under the administration of John F.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Kennedy, extending the restrictions to Cuban imports, based on the Foreign Assistance Act approved by Congress in 1961.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] During the Missile Crisis in 1962, the United States even imposed a naval blockade on Cuba, but this was lifted following the resolution of the crisis.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The embargo, however, remained in place and has been modified on several occasions over the years.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The Cuban Democracy Act of 1992 states that sanctions will continue "so long as it continues to refuse to move toward democratization and greater respect for human rights".
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The UN General Assembly has passed a resolution every year since 1992 condemning the embargo and stating that it violates the Charter of the United Nations and international law.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba considers the embargo a human rights violation.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The impact and effectiveness of the embargo have been subjects of intense debate.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] While some argue it has been "extraordinarily porous" and is not the primary cause of Cuba's economic hardships, others see it as a pressure mechanism aimed at driving change in the Cuban government.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] According to Arturo Lopez Levy, a professor of international relations, it would be more appropriate to refer to the measure as a "blockade" or "siege", as it goes beyond mere trade restrictions.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Other critics of the Cuban government argue that the embargo has been used by the government as an excuse to justify its own economic and political shortcomings.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In 1996, the United States passed the Cuban Liberty and Democratic Solidarity Act, better known as the Helms–Burton Act, which strengthens and continues the United States embargo against Cuba.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In 2009, United States president Barack Obama stated "the United States seeks a new beginning with Cuba", and he reversed the Bush Administration's prohibition on travel and remittances by Cuban-Americans from the United States to Cuba.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In 2014 an agreement between the United States and Cuba, popularly called the "Cuban thaw", brokered in part by Canada and Pope Francis, began the process of restoring international relations between the two countries.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] They agreed to release political prisoners, and in 2015 the United States opened an embassy in Havana. and reestablished diplomatic relations.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In 2015 Obama announced he would remove Cuba from the American government's list of nations that sponsor terrorism, which Cuba reportedly welcomed as "fair".
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] On 17 September 2017, the United States considered closing its Cuban embassy following mysterious medical symptoms experienced by its staff.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The diplomatic relations set in place by Obama were later reversed by the Trump administration, which enacted new rules and re-enforced the business and travel restrictions which were loosened by the Obama administration.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] These sanctions were inherited and strengthened by the Biden administration.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] As of 2018, Cuba spent about US$91.8 million on its armed forces or 2.9% of its GDP.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In 1985, Cuba devoted more than 10% of its GDP to military expenditures.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] During the Cold War, Cuba built up the largest per capita armed forces in Latin America, funded and equipped by the Soviet Union.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] From 1975 until the late 1980s, Soviet military assistance enabled Cuba to upgrade its military capabilities.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] After the loss of Soviet subsidies, Cuba scaled down the numbers of military personnel, from 235,000 in 1994 to about 49,000 in 2021.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In 2017, Cuba signed the UN treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Since signing a defense pact with Belarus in January 2024, Cuba has upgraded its S-125 Pechora air defense systems with Belarusian support, but it does not have a modern networked air defense system.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] According to the Global Peace Index, Cuba has a medium state of peace ranked 102 out of 163 countries.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba is considered a military dictatorship in the Democracy-Dictatorship Index and has been described as "a militarized society" with the armed forces having long been the most powerful institution in the country.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] All law enforcement agencies are maintained under Cuba's Ministry of the Interior, which is supervised by the Revolutionary Armed Forces.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The Intelligence Directorate conducts intelligence operations and maintains close ties with the Russian Federal Security Service.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The US Justice Department considers Cuba a significant counterintelligence threat.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The unconditional release of all political prisoners was called for by the EU.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In July 2010, the unofficial Cuban Human Rights Commission said there were 167 political prisoners in Cuba, a fall from 201 at the start of the year.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The head of the commission stated that long prison sentences were being replaced by harassment and intimidation.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba was ranked 19th by the number of imprisoned journalists of any nation in 2021 according to various sources, including the Committee to Protect Journalists and Human Rights Watch.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba ranks 171st out of 180 on the 2020 World Press Freedom Index.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The Committees for the Defense of the Revolution surveil their neighborhoods for "counter-revolutionary" activity.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Membership is not selective, but leading members are approved by the Cuban Communist Party.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba performs in the top 25% of nations in gender equality.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In 2022 Cuba approved a referendum which amended the Family Code to legalise same-sex marriage and allow surrogate pregnancy and same-sex adoption.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Gender reassignment surgery and transgender hormone therapy are provided free of charge under the national healthcare system.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The government supported the proposed changes, but conservatives and parts of the opposition opposed them.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Official policies of the government from 1959 until the 1990s were hostile towards homosexuality, with the LGBT community marginalized on the basis of heteronormativity, traditional gender roles, and strict criteria for moralism.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The Cuban state asserts its adherence to socialist principles in organizing its largely state-controlled planned economy.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Most of the means of production are owned and run by the government, and most of the labor force is employed by the state.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Recent years have seen a trend toward more private sector employment.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] By 2006, public sector employment was 78% and private sector 22%, compared to 91.8% to 8.2% in 1981.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Since the early 2010s, following the initial market reforms, it has become popular to describe the economy as being, or moving toward, market socialism.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Any firm that hires a Cuban must pay the Cuban government, which in turn pays the employee in Cuban pesos (CUP).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] After a reform in 2021, the minimum monthly wage is about 2100 CUP (US$81), and the median monthly wage is about 4000 CUP (US$155).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] According to Carmelo Mesa-Lago, there is widespread consensus that the policies of the revolutionary government decreased poverty until the end of the Cold War.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Every Cuban household has a ration book (known as libreta) entitling it to a monthly supply of food and other staples, which are provided at nominal cost.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba’s economy is heavily impacted by the US trade embargo, which began in the 1960s.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] According to the Havana Consulting Group, in 2014, remittances to Cuba were more than US$3 million, the seventh highest in Latin America.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In 2019, remittances had grown to US$6,616 million, but dropped down to US$1,967 million in 2020, due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The pandemic devastated Cuba's tourist industry, which along with a tightening of U.S. sanctions, led to large increase in emigration among younger working-age Cubans.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] It has been described as a crisis that is "threatening the stability" of Cuba, which "already has one of the hemisphere's oldest populations".
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] According to a controversial 2023 report by the Cuban Observatory of Human Rights, 88% of Cuban citizens live in extreme poverty.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The report states that Cubans were concerned about food security and the difficulty in acquiring basic goods.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] According to the World Bank, Cuba's GDP per capita was $9,500 as of 2020.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] But according to the CIA World Factbook, it was $12,300 as of 2016.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The United Nations Development Programme gave Cuba a Human Development Index of 0.764 in 2021.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The same United Nations agency estimated the country's Multidimensional Poverty Index of 0.003 in 2023.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In 2005, Cuba had exports of US$2.4 billion, ranking 114 of 226 world countries, and imports of US$6.9 billion, ranking 87 of 226 countries.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Major exports include sugar, nickel, tobacco, fish, medical products, citrus fruits, and coffee; imports include food, fuel, clothing, and machinery.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba presently holds debt in an amount estimated at $13 billion, approximately 38% of GDP.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba's prior 35% supply of the world's export market for sugar has declined to 10% due to a variety of factors, including a global sugar commodity price drop that made Cuba less competitive on world markets.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] It was announced in 2008 that wage caps would be abandoned to improve the nation's productivity.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba's leadership has called for reforms in the country's agricultural system.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In 2008, Raúl Castro began enacting agrarian reforms to boost food production, as at that time 80% of food was imported.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The reforms aim to expand land use and increase efficiency.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Venezuela supplies Cuba with an estimated 110,000 barrels (17,000 m3) of oil per day in exchange for money and the services of some 44,000 Cubans, most of them medical personnel, in Venezuela.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In 2010, Cubans were allowed to build their own houses.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] According to Raúl Castro, they could now improve their houses, but the government would not endorse these new houses or improvements.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] There is virtually no homelessness in Cuba, and 85% of Cubans own their homes and pay no property taxes or mortgage interest.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] On 2 August 2011, *The New York Times* reported that Cuba reaffirmed its intent to legalize "buying and selling" of private property before the year's end.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] According to experts, the private sale of property could "transform Cuba more than any of the economic reforms announced by Cuban leader Raúl Castro's government".
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] It would cut more than one million state jobs, including party bureaucrats who resist the changes.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The reforms created what some call "New Cuban Economy".
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In October 2013, Raúl said he intended to merge the two currencies, but as of August 2016, the dual currency system remains in force.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In 2016, the *Miami Herald* wrote, "... about 27 percent of Cubans earn under $50 per month; 34 percent earn the equivalent of $50 to $100 per month; and 20 percent earn $101 to $200.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In May 2019, Cuba imposed rationing of staples such as chicken, eggs, rice, beans, soap and other basic goods.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] (Some two-thirds of food in the country is imported.) A spokesperson blamed the increased U.S. trade embargo although economists believe that an equally important problem is the massive decline of aid from Venezuela and the failure of Cuba's state-run oil company which had subsidized fuel costs.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In June 2019, the government announced an increase in public sector wages of about 300%, specifically for teachers and health personnel.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In October, the government allowed stores to purchase house equipment and similar items, using international currency, and send it to Cuba by emigration.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The leaders of the government recognized that the new measures were unpopular but necessary to contain the capital flight to other countries as Panamá where Cuban citizens traveled and imported items to resell on the island.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Other measures included allowing private companies to export and import, through state companies, resources to produce products and services in Cuba.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] On 1 January 2021, Cuba's dual currency system was formally ended, and the convertible Cuban peso (CUC) was phased out, leaving the Cuban peso (CUP) as the country's sole currency unit.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuban citizens had until June 2021 to exchange their CUCs.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] However, this devalued the Cuban peso and caused economic problems for people who had been previously paid in CUCs, particularly workers in the tourism industry.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Also, in February, the government dictated new measures to the private sector, with prohibitions for only 124 activities, in areas like national security, health and educational services.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The wages were increased again, between 4 and 9 times, for all the sectors.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Also, new facilities were allowed to the state companies, with much more autonomy.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The first problem with the new reform, in terms of public opinion, were electricity prices, but that was amended quickly.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Other measures corrected were in the prices for private farmers.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cooperatives will play a larger role in the emerging Cuban economy.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The transfer of state-run businesses into cooperatives could result in 20 – 30 percent of Cuba's workers being actively involved in cooperatives.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] All state-run restaurants (over 8,000) will be converted to worker owned cooperatives, and by 2017 the Cuban government expects there to be approximately 10,000 cooperatives operating.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] According to 2019 data, China stands as Cuba's main trading partner, followed by countries such as Spain, the Netherlands, Germany, and Cyprus.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba's main exports include tobacco, sugar, and alcoholic beverages, while it primarily imports chicken meat, wheat, corn, and condensed milk.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba's natural resources include sugar, tobacco, fish, citrus fruits, coffee, beans, rice, potatoes, and livestock.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba's most important mineral resource is nickel, with 21% of total exports in 2011.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The output of Cuba's nickel mines that year was 71,000 tons, approaching 4% of world production.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] As of 2013 its reserves were estimated at 5.5 million tons, over 7% of the world total.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Sherritt International of Canada operates a large nickel mining facility in Moa.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba is also a major producer of refined cobalt, a by-product of nickel mining.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Oil exploration in 2005 by the US Geological Survey revealed that the North Cuba Basin could produce about 4.6 billion barrels (730,000,000 m3) to 9.3 billion barrels (1.48×109 m3) of oil.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In 2006, Cuba started to test-drill these locations for possible exploitation.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Tourism was initially restricted to enclave resorts where tourists would be segregated from Cuban society, referred to as "enclave tourism" and "tourism apartheid".
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Contact between foreign visitors and ordinary Cubans were *de facto* illegal between 1992 and 1997.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The rapid growth of tourism during the Special Period had widespread social and economic repercussions in Cuba, and led to speculation about the emergence of a two-tier economy.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] A study in 2018 indicated that Cuba has a potential for mountaineering activity, and that mountaineering could be a key contributor to tourism, along with other activities, e.g. biking, diving, caving.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Promoting these resources could contribute to regional development, prosperity, and well-being.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The Cuban Justice minister downplays allegations of widespread sex tourism.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] According to a Government of Canada travel advice website, "Cuba is actively working to prevent child sex tourism, and a number of tourists, including Canadians, have been convicted of offenses related to the corruption of minors aged 16 and under.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Its birth rate (9.88 births per thousand population in 2006) is one of the lowest in the Western Hemisphere.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Although the country's population has grown by about four million people since 1961, the rate of growth slowed during that period, and the population began to decline in 2006, due to the country's low fertility rate (1.43 children per woman) coupled with emigration.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Afro-Cubans are descended primarily from the Yoruba people, Bantu people from the Congo basin, Kalabari tribe and Arará from the Dahomey, as well as several thousand North African refugees, most notably the Sahrawi Arabs of Western Sahara.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba's population is therefore multiethnic, and intermarriage between these groups has been widespread across many centuries, producing a significant population of mixed ancestry — not as a product of recent admixture but of long-accumulated intergenerational intermarriage.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Consequently, there is significant discrepancy between different estimates of the country's racial composition.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] A 2014 study based on ancestry-informative markers found that autosomal genetic ancestry in Cuba is 72% European, 20% African, and 8% Indigenous.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The 2002 Cuban census, in which respondents self-identified, found that 65.05% of the population was white, while the 2012 census recorded approximately 27% of Cubans as mestizo o mulato and just under 10% as negro (Black).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The 2012 Cuban census recorded, on the same basis, that 64.1% of the population was white (blanco), 26.6% mestizo o mulato (mixed race), and 9.3% Black (negro).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] As with the 2002 census, these figures reflect self-perception rather than genetic ancestry or externally assigned classification, and have been widely contested by independent researchers who argue that they significantly under-report the Black and mixed-race population.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] These figures also diverge markedly from estimates produced by applying the one-drop rule, the hypodescent convention historically specific to the United States, under which any traceable African ancestry classifies a person as Black.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The Institute for Cuban and Cuban-American Studies at the University of Miami, using that framework, concluded that 62% of Cubans are Black.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] However, the one-drop rule does not reflect Cuban or broader Latin American racial classification.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The Cuban census formally recognises this through its separate mestizo o mulato classification.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Applying a binary Black/white framework derived from U.S. legal and social history to Cuban racial self-identification therefore imposes a classificatory logic that Cuban society does not use and that systematically erases the identities of a substantial portion of the population.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Asians make up about 1% of the population and are largely of Chinese ancestry, followed by Japanese and Filipino.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Many are descendants of farm laborers brought to the island by Spanish and American contractors during the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The current recorded number of Cubans with Chinese ancestry is 114,240.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Immigration and emigration have played a prominent part in Cuba's demographic profile.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Between the 18th and early 20th century, large waves of Canarian, Catalan, Andalusian, Galician, and other Spanish people immigrated to Cuba.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Between 1899 and 1930 alone, nearly one million Spaniards entered Cuba, although many eventually returned to Spain.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Other prominent immigrant groups included French, Portuguese, Italian, Russian, Dutch, Greek, British, and Irish, as well as small number of descendants of U.S. citizens who arrived in Cuba in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] As of 2015, the foreign-born population in Cuba was 13,336 inhabitants per the World Bank data.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Post-revolution Cuba has been characterized by significant levels of emigration, which has led to a large and influential diaspora community.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] During the three decades after January 1959, more than one million Cubans of all social classes—constituting 10% of the total population—emigrated to the United States, a proportion that matches the extent of emigration to the U.S. from the Caribbean as a whole during that period.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Prior to 13 January 2013, Cuban citizens could not travel abroad, leave or return to Cuba without first obtaining official permission along with applying for a government-issued passport and travel visa, which was often denied.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Those who left the country typically did so by sea, in small boats and fragile rafts.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] On 9 September 1994, the U.S. and Cuban governments agreed that the U.S. would grant at least 20,000 visas annually in exchange for Cuba's pledge to prevent further unlawful departures on boats.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In the 2020s Cuba is undergoing its most severe socioeconomic crisis since the fall of the Soviet Union, leading to a record number of Cubans fleeing the island.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The number of Cubans trying to enter the United States, primarily through the Mexican border, surged from 39,000 in 2021 to over 224,000 in 2022.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In 2022, more than 2% of the population (almost 250,000 Cubans out of 11 million) migrated to the United States, and thousands more went to other countries, a number "larger than the 1980 Mariel boatlift and the 1994 Cuban rafter crisis combined", which were Cuba's previous largest migration events.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Many resorted to selling their homes at very low prices to afford one-way flights to Nicaragua, hoping to travel through Mexico to reach the U.S.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Internal migration has led to overpopulation in Havana, resulting in people living in makeshift shelters or overcrowded buildings, some of which are on the brink of collapse.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Regular power outages harken back to the early 1990s, a time when Soviet subsidies ended, plunging the island into economic hardship.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Emigration has continued into the 2020s, with the national population dipping below 10 million for the first time since 1980 in 2025.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] This signifies a 13% loss of population since 2012, when the Cuban population peaked at 11.2 million.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba's "Special Period" saw the country relying heavily on foreign tourism and the earnings of nationals working abroad.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The 2020 pandemic, however, severely affected this revenue stream, decreasing the number of tourists by 75% in 2020.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Monetary reforms in 2021 introduced shocks of inflation, further exacerbating the country's food scarcity and boosting the black market's prominence.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Despite the increasing hardships, the Cuban spirit remains resilient.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Access to the internet since 2018 and widespread use of social media have fueled calls for political and economic liberalization.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The power of the internet was evident during the Cuban protests of 2021, which were promptly suppressed by the police, with many prominent artists and bloggers detained.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] As of 2013 the top emigration destinations were the United States, Spain, Italy, Puerto Rico, and Mexico.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The official language is Spanish, and the vast majority of Cubans speak Cuban Spanish, a form of Caribbean Spanish.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Lucumí, a dialect of the West African language Yoruba, is also used as a liturgical language by practitioners of Santería, and so only as a second language.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Haitian Creole is the second-most spoken language and is spoken by Haitian immigrants and their descendants.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Other languages spoken by immigrants include Galician and Corsican.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Russian will be the first foreign language taught in schools, as of the 2026-2027 school year.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Religious freedom increased through the 1980s, with the government amending the constitution in 1992 to drop the state's characterization as atheistic.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In 2010, the Pew Forum estimated that religious affiliation is 59.2% Christian, 23% unaffiliated, 17.4% folk religion (such as Santería), and the remaining 0.4% consisting of other religions.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In a 2015 survey sponsored by Univision, 44% of Cubans said they were not religious, and 9% did not give an answer while only 34% said they were Christian.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Roman Catholicism is the largest religion, with its origins in Spanish colonization.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Despite less than half of the population identifying as Catholics in 2006, it nonetheless remains the dominant faith.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Pope John Paul II and Pope Benedict XVI visited Cuba in 1998 and 2011, respectively, and Pope Francis visited in 2015.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Prior to each papal visit, the government pardoned prisoners as a humanitarian gesture.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The government's relaxation of restrictions on house churches in the 1990s led to an explosion of Pentecostalism, with some groups claiming as many as 100,000 members.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] However, Evangelical Protestant denominations, organized into the umbrella Cuban Council of Churches, remain much more vibrant and powerful.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Several well-known Cuban religious figures have operated outside the island, including the humanitarian and author Jorge Armando Pérez.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The religious landscape of is strongly defined by syncretisms of various kinds.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Christianity is often practiced in tandem with Santería, a mixture of Catholicism and mostly African faiths, which include a number of cults.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] La Virgen de la Caridad del Cobre (the Virgin of *Cobre*) is the Catholic patroness of Cuba, and a symbol of Cuban culture.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In Santería, she has been syncretized with the goddess Oshun.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] A breakdown of the followers of Afro-Cuban religions showed that most practitioners of Palo Mayombe were black and dark brown-skinned, most practitioners of Vodú were medium brown and light brown-skinned, and most practitioners of Santería were light brown and white-skinned.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba hosts small communities of Jews (500 in 2012), Muslims (6,000 in 2011), and members of the Baháʼí Faith.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The University of Havana was founded in 1728, and there are several other well-established colleges and universities.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In 1957, just before Castro came to power, the literacy rate was as low as fourth in Latin America at 76% according to the United Nations, yet higher than in Spain.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Castro created an entirely state-operated system and banned private institutions.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] School attendance is compulsory from ages six to the end of basic secondary education (normally at age 15), and all students, regardless of age or gender, wear school uniforms with the color denoting grade level.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Primary education lasts for six years, secondary education is divided into basic and pre-university education.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba's literacy rate of 99.8 percent is eight points higher than the Caribbean average and the tenth-highest globally, largely due to the provision of free education at every level.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The high school graduation rate is 94 percent.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Higher education is provided by universities, higher institutes, higher pedagogical institutes, and higher polytechnic institutes.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The Ministry of Higher Education operates a distance education program that provides regular afternoon and evening courses in rural areas for agricultural workers.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Education has a strong political and ideological emphasis, and students progressing to higher education are expected to have a commitment to the goals of Cuba.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba has provided free education to foreign nationals from disadvantaged backgrounds at the Latin American School of Medicine.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] After the revolution, Cuba established a free public health system.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba's life expectancy at birth is 80.1 years (77.8 for males and 82.6 for females), ranked 58th in the world and 5th in the Americas.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Historically, Cuba has ranked high in numbers of medical personnel and has made significant contributions to world health since the 19th century.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba has universal health care, and despite persistent shortages of medical supplies, there is no shortage of medical personnel.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Primary care is available throughout the island, and infant and maternal mortality rates compare favorably with those in developed nations.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] That an impoverished nation like Cuba has health outcomes rivaling the developed world is referred to by researchers as the Cuban Health Paradox.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba ranks 29th on the 2024 Bloomberg Healthiest Country Index, the highest ranking of a developing country.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The healthcare system, renowned for its medical services, has emphasized the export of health professionals through international missions, aiding global health efforts.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] However, while these missions generate significant revenue and serve as a tool for political influence, domestically, Cuba faces challenges including medication shortages and disparities between medical services for locals and foreigners.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Despite the income from these missions, only a small fraction of the national budget has been allocated to public health, underscoring contrasting priorities within the nation's healthcare strategy.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Disease and infant mortality increased in the 1960s immediately after the revolution, when half of Cuba's 6,000 doctors left the country.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Recovery occurred by the 1980s, and the country's health care has been widely praised.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The Communist government stated that universal health care was a priority of state planning and progress was made in rural areas.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] After the revolution, the government increased rural hospitals from one to 62.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Like the rest of the Cuban economy, medical care suffered from severe material shortages following the end of Soviet subsidies in 1991, and a tightening of the U.S. embargo in 1992.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Challenges include low salaries for doctors, poor facilities, poor provision of equipment, and the frequent absence of essential drugs.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuba has the highest doctor-to-population ratio in the world and has sent thousands of doctors to more than 40 countries around the world.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] According to the World Health Organization, Cuba is "known the world over for its ability to train excellent doctors and nurses who can then go out to help other countries in need".
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In 2014 there were around 50,000 Cuban-trained health care workers aiding 66 nations.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Cuban physicians have played a leading role in combating the Ebola virus epidemic in West Africa.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Preventative medicine is very important within the Cuban medical system, which provides citizens with easy to obtain regular health checks.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Import and export of pharmaceutical drugs is done by the Quimefa Pharmaceutical Business Group (FARMACUBA) under the Ministry of Basic Industry.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] This group also provides technical information for the production of these drugs.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] Isolated from the West by the US embargo, Cuba developed the successful lung cancer vaccine, Cimavax, which is now available to US researchers for the first time, along with other novel Cuban cancer treatments.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The vaccine has been available for free to the Cuban population since 2011.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] According to Roswell Park Comprehensive Cancer Center CEO Candace Johnson: "They've had to do more with less, so they've had to be even more innovative with how they approach things.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] For over 40 years, they have had a preeminent immunology community." During the thaw in Cuba–U.S. relations, many U.S. lung cancer patients traveled to Cuba to receive vaccine treatment.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] The end of the thaw under the Trump Administration resulted in a tightening of travel restrictions, making it harder for U.S. citizens to travel to Cuba for treatment.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p02] In 2015, Cuba became the first country to eradicate mother-to-child transmission of HIV and syphilis, a milestone hailed by the World Health Organization as "one of the greatest public health achievements possible".
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Cuban culture is influenced by its melting pot of cultures, primarily those of Spain, West Africa, and the indigenous Guanahatabey and Taíno.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] After the 1959 revolution, the government started a national literacy campaign, offered free education to all and established rigorous sports, ballet, and music programs.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Cuban architecture reflects a range of historical influences, with its foundations rooted primarily in the Spanish colonial period.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Early settlements, or villas, were typically organized around a central church, surrounded by residential structures.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] These homes often featured interior courtyards and iron grilles, a characteristic element of colonial domestic architecture.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Spanish Baroque architecture played a significant role during this era, exemplified by religious buildings such as the Basílica de San Francisco in Havana.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] In response to the threat of piracy, large fortifications were also constructed, contributing to the island's defensive infrastructure.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Several historic urban centers developed during the colonial period, many of which have been recognized for their architectural and cultural value.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Notable examples include Havana, Camagüey, Cienfuegos and Trinidad, all of which are inscribed as UNESCO World Heritage Sites.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] These cities display a variety of architectural styles, ranging from Baroque and Neoclassical to eclectic influences.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Additional towns such as Santiago de Cuba, Matanzas or Remedios also preserve significant colonial-era architecture.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] During the Republican period (1902–1959), Cuban architecture saw the construction of prominent public and commercial buildings.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Notable examples include El Capitolio, inspired by the United States Capitol, as well as modern high-rise structures such as the FOCSA Building and the Habana Hilton (later renamed Habana Libre).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Architect Antonio Quintana Simonetti emerged as a leading figure during the mid-20th century, contributing to the development of modern Cuban architecture.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Following revolution, architectural styles were heavily influenced by Soviet urban planning, emphasizing functionality, uniformity, and efficiency.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Residential neighborhoods constructed during this period reflected the characteristics of socialist realism seen in cities like Moscow and Minsk.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] After the dissolution of the Soviet Union and the end of the Cold War, architecture became more varied.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] The 1990s and early 21st century saw a rise in the construction of luxury hotels, incorporating modern materials such as glass and steel, and reflecting global architectural trends similar to those found in cities like Mexico City, Caracas, and New York.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Cuban literature began to find its voice in the early 19th century.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Dominant themes of independence and freedom were exemplified by José Martí, who led the Modernist movement in Cuban literature.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Writers such as Nicolás Guillén and José Z.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Tallet focused on literature as social protest.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] The poetry and novels of Dulce María Loynaz and José Lezama Lima have been influential.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Romanticist Miguel Barnet, who wrote *Everyone Dreamed of Cuba*, reflects a more melancholy Cuba.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Alejo Carpentier was important in the magic realism movement.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] However, some Cuban writers continue living and writing in Cuba, including Nancy Morejón.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Cuban music is rich and is the most commonly known expression of Cuban culture.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] The central form of this music is *son*, which has been the basis of many other musical styles like "Danzón de nuevo ritmo", mambo, cha-cha-chá and salsa music.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Rumba ("de cajón o de solar") music originated in the early Afro-Cuban culture, mixed with Spanish elements of style.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] The tres was invented in Cuba from Spanish cordophone instruments models (the instrument is actually a fusion of elements from the Spanish guitar and lute).
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Other traditional Cuban instruments are of African origin, Taíno origin, or both, such as the maracas, güiro, marímbula and various wooden drums including the mayohuacán.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Popular Cuban music of all styles has been enjoyed and praised widely across the world.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Cuban classical music, which includes music with strong African and European influences, and features symphonic works as well as music for soloists, has received international acclaim thanks to composers like Ernesto Lecuona.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Havana was the heart of the rap scene in Cuba when it began in the 1990s.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] The culture encompasses a wide range of dance forms.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Danzón was the official musical genre and dance of Cuba.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Mambo music and dance developed originally in Cuba, with further significant developments by Cuban musicians in Mexico and the US.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] The cha-cha-cha is another dance of Cuban origin, while the Cuban bolero originated in Santiago de Cuba in the 19th century.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Concert dance is supported by the government and includes internationally renowned companies such as the Ballet Nacional de Cuba.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Salsa dancing originated in Cuba, and Cuban salsa is danced around the world.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] ETECSA opened 118 cybercafes across the country in 2013.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] The government of Cuba provides an online encyclopedia website called EcuRed that operates in a "wiki" format.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Internet access is controlled, and e-mail is closely monitored.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Since 2018, access to Internet by mobile data is available.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] In 2019, 7.1 million Cubans could access the Internet.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] The prices of connections, since WiFi zones, or mobile data, or from houses through "Nauta Hogar" service have been decreasing, especially since the economic reform of January 2021, when all the salaries increased by at least 5 times, and the prices of Internet remain in the same point.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] In 2024, it was reported that 8.19 million Cuban people have Internet access.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] There were 6.68 million mobile connections in Cuba in January 2021.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Cuban cuisine is a fusion of Spanish and Caribbean cuisines.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Cuban recipes share spices and techniques with Spanish cooking, with some Caribbean influence in spice and flavor.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Food rationing, which has been the norm for the last four decades, restricts the common availability of these dishes.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] The traditional meal is not served in courses; all food items are served at the same time.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] The typical meal could consist of plantains, black beans and rice, *ropa vieja* (shredded beef), Cuban bread, pork with onions, and tropical fruits.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Black beans and rice, referred to as *moros y cristianos* (or *moros* for short), and plantains are staples.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Many of the meat dishes are cooked slowly with light sauces.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Garlic, cumin, oregano, and bay leaves are the dominant spices.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Due to historical associations with the United States, many Cubans participate in sports that are popular in North America, rather than sports traditionally played in other Latin American nations.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Other popular sports include volleyball, boxing, athletics, wrestling, basketball and water sports.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Cuba is a dominant force in amateur boxing, consistently achieving high medal tallies in major international competitions.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Boxers Rances Barthelemy and Erislandy Lara defected to the U.S. and Mexico respectively.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Cuba also provides a national team that competes in the Olympic Games.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/cuba-p03] Capablanca was a Cuban world chess champion from 1921 to 1927.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/domo-bolivariano-de-barquisimeto] Domo Bolivariano has been used as the home arena of the Venezuelan League professional basketball club, Guaros de Lara.
[src:2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship/domo-bolivariano-de-barquisimeto] The arena hosted the Grand Finals of the 2016 FIBA Americas League, and the 2017 FIBA Americas League.
